WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:12.240
Young adult Ailey readers, The Hound of the Baskervilles, Sir Arthur Conan Doyle, copyright

00:12.240 --> 00:40.480
Ailey 2010 Chapter 1 James Mortimer comes to Baker Street

00:40.720 --> 00:49.200
Mr Sherlock Holmes was at the breakfast table. I was by the fire. I had a walking stick in my hand.

00:50.080 --> 00:57.440
It was a stranger's stick. Yesterday a stranger came to the house when Holmes and I were out.

00:58.320 --> 01:06.880
The stranger left his stick. There was some writing on it to James Mortimer MRCS

01:06.960 --> 01:14.160
from his friends of the CCH 1884. Who is the stick Watson?

01:15.920 --> 01:19.200
But you can't see me. How do you know what I'm doing?

01:20.480 --> 01:27.920
I can see your reflection in the window, said Holmes. But tell me Watson, what do you think of our

01:27.920 --> 01:34.640
visitor? We didn't meet him, so his stick is an important clue for us. What do you think?

01:34.640 --> 01:43.680
I think, I said, that Mortimer is a successful doctor. I know that from the letters MRCS,

01:43.680 --> 01:53.200
only a doctor can use those letters. He's quite old and he's probably a country doctor. He walks

01:53.200 --> 02:00.080
a lot because I can see that Dr Mortimer uses this stick a lot. Excellent, said Holmes.

02:00.240 --> 02:11.280
Then we have friends of the CCH. A club, I think. Perhaps he helped them and they gave him the stick.

02:11.280 --> 02:21.120
Congratulations Watson. However, Holmes continued, I'm sorry, but most of your ideas are wrong.

02:21.120 --> 02:29.920
Wrong? Well, he's a country doctor and he walks a lot, you're right. But I think the

02:30.000 --> 02:36.720
CCH is probably Charing Cross Hospital, not a club. I also think he's a young doctor.

02:37.440 --> 02:43.280
He left the hospital and went to work in the country. The stick was a present when he left

02:43.280 --> 02:49.920
the hospital. Then, of course, he has a dog. Look at the stick. His dog carries it.

02:50.720 --> 03:00.080
I laughed. I looked in my medical dictionary. Here he is. Mortimer, James. MRCS 1882,

03:00.080 --> 03:08.400
Grimpen, Dartmoor, Devon. Doctor from 1882 to 1884 at Charing Cross Hospital.

03:09.440 --> 03:15.680
See you, Watson? A hospital, not a club. But you're right. He is a country doctor.

03:16.640 --> 03:25.280
And the dog? The dog is black and white. But Holmes, please, how can you possibly know that?

03:26.560 --> 03:34.400
Well, I can see the dog outside the window. And here is Doctor Mortimer now. But what does he want?

03:35.760 --> 03:44.960
Come in. Our visitor was tall and thin with a long nose. He wore glasses. He was very happy

03:45.040 --> 03:48.080
to see us. And very happy to see his stick.

03:49.920 --> 03:55.920
Thank you. He said as Holmes gave him his stick. And this was a present when I left Charing Cross

03:55.920 --> 04:04.640
Hospital. Are you Mr Sherlock Holmes? Yes. And this is my friend, Doctor Watson. I'm very pleased

04:04.640 --> 04:11.920
to meet you. You are very interesting. You have a very beautiful skull. You have an excellent

04:12.000 --> 04:20.400
Dolicoscephalic skull. Dolicoscephalic. That's a very interesting word. You know a lot about skulls.

04:21.440 --> 04:30.400
You clearly love your work, said Holmes. Please, sit down. So, why did you come here yesterday?

04:31.360 --> 04:36.960
Why are you here again today? You didn't come to look at my skull, I'm sure.

04:37.840 --> 04:44.480
No, I have an interesting problem and I need your help. I've got a document in my pocket.

04:45.840 --> 04:55.680
I saw it when you came in, said Holmes. It's an old one, probably about 1730. But how do you know that?

04:56.800 --> 05:03.360
You love your work and I love mine. All good detectives can look at a document and give it a date.

05:04.160 --> 05:12.000
Am I right? To ten or fifteen years? Yes. The date on the document is 1742.

05:12.720 --> 05:20.000
It's a Baskerville family document. My friend and patient Charles Baskerville gave it to me

05:20.000 --> 05:26.160
before he died. He wanted me to look after it. This document was very important to him.

05:26.800 --> 05:34.400
He was very superstitious. It's about the curse of the Baskerville family. Can I read it to you?

05:36.320 --> 05:43.760
Holmes sat back in his chair and closed his eyes. He looked bored. Dr Mortimer began.

05:45.520 --> 05:53.840
Baskerville Hall 1742 to all Baskevilles. Read this story carefully. Do what it says.

05:53.840 --> 06:04.480
This happened in 1647 when Hugo Baskerville lived at Baskerville Hall. He was a very bad man.

06:04.480 --> 06:14.240
One day he kidnapped a young girl from her home. He took her to a room upstairs but she escaped.

06:14.240 --> 06:23.600
She ran out of the house and ran and ran across the moor. Hugo was very angry. He followed her with

06:23.600 --> 06:32.880
his dogs. His friends followed too but Hugo was very fast. When Hugo's friends found the girl

06:33.840 --> 06:41.680
she was dead. They saw Hugo's dogs and they saw Hugo's body. He was dead too.

06:42.720 --> 06:50.960
His friends also saw a large black animal in the distance. It was the killer. It was a dog

06:51.600 --> 06:57.760
but it wasn't an ordinary dog. It was a strange and terrible hound.

06:59.440 --> 07:06.880
Many of our family die in strange and terrible ways. This hound follows the Baskerville family.

07:07.760 --> 07:15.040
This is why I'm writing this story. I must tell you, never go out on the moor at night.

07:15.920 --> 07:24.400
Dr Mortimer finished the story. Then Dr Mortimer took out a newspaper report from his pocket.

07:25.360 --> 07:33.600
Holmes looked bored again. Now Mr Holmes, here is something from the Dartmoor Chronicle of May

07:33.600 --> 07:39.200
the 14th this year. It's about Charles Baskerville and the story of his death.

07:40.080 --> 07:49.600
Sir Charles Baskerville from Baskerville Hall died on May the 4th. He only lived here for

07:49.600 --> 07:56.880
two years but people liked him very much. He worked in South Africa, made a lot of money

07:56.880 --> 08:01.680
and then he returned to Devon. He helped a lot of people here.

08:03.440 --> 08:08.800
People are talking about the curse of the Baskervilles and the story of the hound.

08:09.520 --> 08:18.080
But the facts are simple. His servants, Mr and Mrs Barrymore and his doctor, Dr James Mortimer,

08:18.080 --> 08:23.200
all say that he had a weak heart. The post-mortem showed that this was true.

08:24.720 --> 08:31.920
Barrymore told our journalist about the night of May the 4th. Sir Charles wanted to go to London

08:31.920 --> 08:38.880
on the morning of May the 5th. After dinner he went for a walk. He always went out before bed

08:38.880 --> 08:46.880
to smoke. He didn't return. At twelve o'clock I was worried so I went to look for Sir Charles.

08:47.680 --> 08:52.720
I followed his footprints. There were a lot of footprints by the gate to the moor.

08:53.440 --> 08:56.560
Then the footprints went to the end of the path.

08:58.720 --> 09:05.520
There is one strange fact from Barrymore's story. After the moor gate the footprints were

09:05.520 --> 09:13.280
different. Sir Charles walked on tiptoe. Sir Charles' relative, Mr Henry Baskerville,

09:13.280 --> 09:18.640
is in Canada. All of us at the Dartmoor Chronicle hope to see him here soon.

09:19.520 --> 09:22.480
We hope he can continue Sir Charles' good work.

09:24.880 --> 09:28.160
Dr Mortimer put the newspaper back in his pocket.

09:29.040 --> 09:36.560
Those facts are public, Mr Holmes. There are other facts too. Not many people live on the moor.

09:37.280 --> 09:44.560
The houses are all quite far apart. The only educated men are Mr Franklin of Laughter Hall

09:44.560 --> 09:50.640
and Mr Stapleton. He is a naturalist. But the people who live near each other spend a lot of

09:50.640 --> 09:57.680
time together. I spend a lot of time with Sir Charles. His stories about South Africa were

09:57.680 --> 10:04.480
very interesting. I was also his doctor. He believed in the curse of the hound of the

10:04.480 --> 10:11.760
Baskervilles. He was terrified of it. He often heard the howl of a dog at night.

10:12.640 --> 10:18.240
One evening I went to his house. When I arrived I saw him at the door.

10:19.040 --> 10:26.480
His face was white. He looked terrified. I followed his eyes and saw a large black

10:26.480 --> 10:34.960
animal. It was the size of a small cow. I saw it clearly. It was something bad,

10:34.960 --> 10:41.680
something supernatural. Sir Charles' fear of the family curse was bad for him.

10:42.560 --> 10:47.760
I suggested a very long visit to London. He needed to rest.

10:49.120 --> 10:55.680
On the night of Sir Charles' death Barry Moore called me. I also followed the footprints down

10:55.680 --> 11:04.080
the path. I saw Barry Moore's footprints too. Then, near the body, I saw other footprints.

11:05.120 --> 11:08.320
Barry Moore didn't see them. But I did.

11:10.160 --> 11:17.840
Were they a man's footprints or a woman's? Said Holmes. Dr Mortimer spoke very quietly.

11:18.320 --> 11:25.120
Mr. Holmes, they were the footprints of a gigantic hound.

11:27.120 --> 11:32.320
Why didn't Barry Moore see the footprints? They weren't near the body.

11:33.200 --> 11:38.480
What was the weather like that night? It was cold, but it didn't rain.

11:39.680 --> 11:47.200
Can you describe the path? There are trees on each side. There is a gate on the left of the

11:47.920 --> 11:56.080
path. It goes out to the maw. So, can you only get to the path from the house or from the gate?

11:56.720 --> 12:04.000
Yes, I see. Were the footprints on the left of the path too? Yes, they were.

12:05.440 --> 12:11.360
Very interesting. And was the gate closed? And is it very high?

12:12.160 --> 12:18.640
Yes, it was closed and locked. But it's not very high. It's easy to climb over it.

12:20.080 --> 12:28.160
Did you see any footprints by the gate? I'm not sure. I think I only saw Sir Charles' footprints.

12:28.160 --> 12:32.000
There were a lot of them. I know he was there for about ten minutes.

12:33.280 --> 12:39.920
How do you know that? There was a match and part of a cigarette. He smoked a cigarette there.

12:41.920 --> 12:45.360
Excellent. Congratulations. You're a detective too.

12:46.640 --> 12:50.480
So, you want me to investigate Sir Charles' death?

12:51.600 --> 12:57.360
Not really. I think Sir Charles died of fright. My problem is with Sir Henry Baskerville.

12:58.000 --> 13:03.760
He arrives at Waterloo station at one o'clock today. He's the only heir to Baskerville Hall.

13:04.400 --> 13:09.360
I think he wants to go to the hall. But I don't think the hall is safe for him.

13:10.240 --> 13:17.920
I don't know what to do. Go to Waterloo station. Meet Henry Baskerville and take him to his hotel.

13:18.640 --> 13:24.800
I need time to think about this. Come here tomorrow at ten o'clock. Brings a Henry with you.

13:25.920 --> 13:33.200
But before you go, one more question. Before Sir Charles' death, how many people saw this

13:33.200 --> 13:41.760
hound on the moor? Three people saw it. Did anyone see it after Sir Charles died? No.

13:43.840 --> 13:46.320
Thank you, Dr Mortimer. A good morning.

13:48.560 --> 13:52.880
Holmes returned to his chair. He looked pleased about this new case.

13:54.240 --> 13:59.680
I need time alone. I need to think Watson. Can you go out until this evening?

14:00.320 --> 14:08.800
Then we can talk about this case together. I spent the day at my club. I returned at about nine o'clock.

14:10.080 --> 14:17.360
So, you went to your club for the day. Yes, but how? He laughed.

14:19.360 --> 14:26.320
Elementary, Watson. It rained all morning and all afternoon. You're completely dry.

14:26.320 --> 14:31.520
Look, your hat and your shoes are dry. So it's clear that you spent the day inside.

14:32.800 --> 14:36.560
As for me, I studied this map of Dartmoor all afternoon.

14:38.240 --> 14:46.000
He put the map on the table and showed me. This is Baskerville Hall. Can you see the trees around it?

14:46.960 --> 14:53.200
And this is the path where Sir Charles died. This is the village of Grimpen.

14:54.080 --> 14:59.920
That's where Dr Mortimer lives. Here is laughter hall. Mr Franklin lives there.

15:00.560 --> 15:06.400
And this is probably Mr Stapleton's house. You can see that they are all quite far apart.

15:07.840 --> 15:14.400
Over here, there are some farmhouses. Then here, 14 miles away, is Prince Town Prison.

15:15.200 --> 15:16.800
All around, there's the moor.

15:16.800 --> 15:24.080
It's a lonely place. Do you think Dr Mortimer is right, Holmes?

15:24.080 --> 15:26.960
Do you think the Hound is a supernatural animal?

15:28.320 --> 15:33.200
And Dr Mortimer thinks that it's supernatural. He believes the family curse.

15:34.160 --> 15:40.240
I believe in facts, Watson, not stories. Our first job is to look for the facts.

15:41.200 --> 15:47.040
Did Sir Charles die because of his heart? Or did someone kill him?

15:48.160 --> 15:53.120
Chapter 2. The letter, the shoes, and the man with the beard.

15:54.720 --> 16:00.000
Well, Watson, you know the results of my work today. What about you?

16:00.880 --> 16:07.840
Did you think about our new case, said Holmes? Yes, I did. I thought a lot about it.

16:08.720 --> 16:14.640
There are some things I don't understand. Why did Sir Charles' footprints change?

16:15.520 --> 16:24.880
Why did he walk on tiptoe? He didn't. He ran. When you run, your footprints change. Sir Charles

16:24.880 --> 16:33.200
ran, Watson. He ran for his life. He was terrified. But what did he run away from?

16:34.160 --> 16:40.800
Now that's the problem. It's strange. He didn't run in the direction of the house.

16:40.800 --> 16:46.480
He ran away from it. Help was that the house? But he ran away.

16:48.000 --> 16:55.520
And why did he wait at the gate? Did he want to meet someone? Sir Charles was old and quite ill.

16:56.080 --> 17:01.600
It was a cold night. It seems strange that he stopped for a long time by the gate.

17:02.400 --> 17:06.320
Remember, a doctor Mortimer told us about the match and the cigarette.

17:06.960 --> 17:12.880
He had time to smoke a cigarette there. 10 minutes is a long time for an ill man.

17:14.160 --> 17:20.560
But he went out every evening. Yes, but I'm sure he didn't wait by the more gate every evening.

17:21.360 --> 17:28.880
He was afraid of the more. But that night he waited there. It was the night before his trip to London.

17:29.520 --> 17:32.640
Ah, Watson. I think I'm beginning to understand something.

17:33.360 --> 17:38.640
Pass me my vial in my friend. Let's wait until our meeting with Sir Henry Baskerville in the morning.

17:41.120 --> 17:48.320
Our visitors arrived at exactly 10 o'clock. Sir Henry Baskerville was a small man with dark eyes.

17:48.960 --> 17:56.160
He was about 30 years old and was strong and healthy. He was a gentleman. But it was also

17:56.160 --> 18:01.840
clear that he liked spending time outside. I'm very pleased to meet you, Mr Holmes.

18:02.480 --> 18:07.120
Can I show you something? It's a strange letter. I got it this morning.

18:08.960 --> 18:16.320
Sir Henry put the letter on the table. The address said Sir Henry Baskerville Northumberland Hotel.

18:17.840 --> 18:24.080
That's very interesting. Did anyone know you were at the Northumberland Hotel, said Holmes?

18:24.960 --> 18:33.360
No, Dr Mortimer and I only decided when I arrived at the station. Hmm, someone followed you.

18:35.120 --> 18:42.560
Holmes looked at the letter. There was only one sentence. Almost all the words were from a newspaper.

18:43.920 --> 18:49.120
You are in danger. Keep away from the more.

18:49.440 --> 18:54.480
Only the word more wasn't from the newspaper.

18:56.560 --> 19:03.120
Very interesting. Have you got yesterday's Times Watson? I gave the newspaper to him.

19:04.720 --> 19:12.480
Yes. Here, can you see, these words are all on the front page. The words in this letter come from the Times.

19:12.800 --> 19:20.160
Dr Mortimer was very surprised. And how did you know which newspaper to look at?

19:21.600 --> 19:28.320
Well, as I said yesterday, we both love our work. You know all about skulls because it's your

19:28.320 --> 19:37.120
special hobby. This is my special hobby. Most newspapers have a style. The Times front page is very obvious.

19:37.440 --> 19:44.880
So, someone cut out this message, said Sir Henry. But why did he write the word more?

19:46.640 --> 19:53.040
Because it wasn't in the newspaper. The word more is unusual. That's why he wrote it.

19:53.840 --> 20:01.680
And another thing, the address is in bad writing. But people who read the Times are usually educated

20:01.680 --> 20:10.160
people. Our writer is an educated man, but he wants to seem uneducated. Why does he want to

20:10.160 --> 20:17.440
hide his writing from you, Sir Henry? Does he think you know his writing? And another thing,

20:18.160 --> 20:26.160
I also think our man wrote this in a hotel. How can you possibly know that, said Dr Mortimer?

20:26.960 --> 20:33.840
You can see that the writer didn't know the pen. The pen and the ink gave our writer some problems.

20:33.840 --> 20:40.880
That's why I think he was in a hotel. Yes. Watson, we must look in the hotel's near Charing Cross.

20:40.880 --> 20:48.480
Somewhere near there, there's a bin. In it, there's a copy of the Times. The words in this letter are

20:48.480 --> 20:54.400
missing from it. Sir Henry, did anyone follow you yesterday? I didn't see anyone.

20:55.360 --> 21:02.080
But a strange thing happened. I lost a shoe. They were new shoes. I bought them yesterday

21:02.080 --> 21:08.160
afternoon. I put them in my wardrobe. This morning, there was only one shoe there.

21:10.320 --> 21:16.160
But why did anybody steal a shoe? And why one shoe? I said,

21:16.160 --> 21:25.520
I know, said Sir Henry. It's very strange. But now you must tell me, why am I here? What's happening?

21:27.680 --> 21:36.240
Tell him, said Holmes. Dr Mortimer read the Baskerville family document and the newspaper report to Sir Henry.

21:37.840 --> 21:43.360
Well, said Sir Henry. Strange things are happening at Baskerville Hall.

21:44.320 --> 21:49.680
And now there's this strange letter. Does someone want to stop me from going to the hall?

21:51.040 --> 21:58.080
I don't know, said Dr Mortimer. Perhaps someone knows the more is dangerous. Perhaps he wants to help you.

21:59.600 --> 22:05.600
Holmes stood up. That's the problem. Is Baskerville Hall safe?

22:06.560 --> 22:12.960
Well, I want to go to my family home, said Sir Henry. No one can stop me.

22:14.240 --> 22:20.320
I need time to think. Come to my hotel at two o'clock. Then I can tell you what I want to do.

22:22.160 --> 22:26.720
Dr Mortimer and Henry Baskerville left our house in Baker Street.

22:27.760 --> 22:32.640
Suddenly, Holmes jumped up. Quick Watson, let's follow them.

22:33.440 --> 22:43.440
We ran outside. We saw them about a hundred yards away. They walked into Oxford Street and then into Regent Street.

22:44.240 --> 22:49.280
They stopped and looked in a shop window. A cab opposite stopped too.

22:50.720 --> 22:54.320
That cab's following them, Watson. Quick, let's see who's in it.

22:54.320 --> 23:03.840
In the cab, I could see a man with a big black beard. But the man saw us and the cab drove quickly away.

23:04.880 --> 23:07.600
Holmes chased it, but the cab was too fast.

23:09.280 --> 23:15.600
It was cab 2704. Did you see the man, Watson? Yes, he had a beard.

23:17.040 --> 23:19.440
I followed Holmes into an office building.

23:20.320 --> 23:27.520
Where's Cartwright, the message boy? Ah, there he is. Cartwright, come here, boy. Bring me a hotel directory.

23:28.640 --> 23:30.560
The boy ran quickly to Holmes.

23:31.600 --> 23:36.880
Now, Cartwright, here are the names of 23 hotels near Charing Cross.

23:37.520 --> 23:46.400
Visit them all. Tell the porters that you want to see the bins from yesterday. Tell them that a client lost an important telegram.

23:47.040 --> 23:52.400
Do you understand? Yes, sir. Cartwright was an intelligent boy.

23:54.640 --> 24:01.920
But you're really looking for a copy of yesterday's times. You're looking for a copy with some words missing.

24:03.040 --> 24:11.840
Go now. And good luck. Now, Watson, let's go to the cab office. I want to leave a message for the driver of cab number 2704.

24:12.720 --> 24:15.040
Then let's go to Sir Henry's hotel.

24:17.040 --> 24:21.520
Sir Henry Baskerville is waiting for you, said the hotel receptionist.

24:22.880 --> 24:27.920
We went upstairs. Sir Henry was there. He was very angry.

24:28.960 --> 24:40.640
Another shoe, he shouted. Why is someone stealing my shoes? Yesterday they stole one of my new brown shoes. This morning they stole one of my old black shoes.

24:41.440 --> 24:44.160
How strange, said Holmes.

24:45.600 --> 24:49.760
We went into Sir Henry's sitting room and we talked about his plans.

24:50.960 --> 24:55.360
Now, Sir Henry, what do you want to do, said Holmes?

24:56.480 --> 24:59.680
I want to go to Baskerville Hall at the end of this week.

25:00.960 --> 25:07.840
I think it's a good idea. You're in danger in London. This morning someone followed you.

25:08.720 --> 25:15.120
Dr. Mortimer was very surprised. We didn't see anyone. Did you see the person?

25:16.160 --> 25:24.640
No, I didn't. But he had a big black beard. Do you know anyone on Dartmoor with a big black beard?

25:26.640 --> 25:33.680
Barrymore. He's such a child's butler. He's got a big black beard. But he's at Baskerville Hall.

25:33.680 --> 25:41.840
Are you sure? Let's check. Sir Henry, you must send a telegram to Barrymore.

25:41.840 --> 25:50.640
Say, is everything ready for my arrival? Say that the telegram must go to Barrymore and only Barrymore.

25:51.280 --> 25:58.560
Ask him to send you an answer. Now, Dr. Mortimer, did Sir Charles leave the Barrymore's any money in his will?

25:59.520 --> 26:02.400
Yes, he left them 500 pounds.

26:03.360 --> 26:06.400
Did they know about this before Sir Charles died?

26:07.280 --> 26:10.880
Yes, they did. Sir Charles often talked about his will.

26:11.680 --> 26:17.120
Sir Charles gave a lot of money to a lot of people. He was a very kind man.

26:18.240 --> 26:25.680
When Sir Charles died, he had nearly a million pounds. Now Sir Henry has a lot of money.

26:26.640 --> 26:31.120
Hmm. Very rich. Very interesting.

26:32.560 --> 26:39.680
And who is Sir Henry's heir? Sir Charles' second brother died when he was young.

26:40.400 --> 26:42.400
Sir Henry here is his son.

26:43.840 --> 26:49.760
Roger Baskerville was Sir Charles' third brother. He was a dangerous man like Hugo.

26:50.400 --> 26:56.400
He had problems with the police, so he went to Central America. He died there.

26:57.360 --> 27:04.000
He didn't marry before he died. Sir Charles' brothers are dead, so Sir Henry is the only heir.

27:05.760 --> 27:12.720
I see. Well, Sir Henry, you can go to Baskerville Hall, but not alone.

27:13.520 --> 27:18.000
I'm investigating something for a famous person, so I can't come myself.

27:18.000 --> 27:21.920
Oh, Watson, you must go. Yes, of course, I said.

27:23.440 --> 27:28.400
We walked towards the door. Suddenly, Sir Henry shouted,

27:29.040 --> 27:32.160
my new shoe. There it is under that chair.

27:34.160 --> 27:42.080
Strange, said Dr Mortimer. We searched this room very carefully before lunch. There wasn't a shoe here then.

27:42.080 --> 27:49.520
Holmes and I went home. In the cab, I thought about the last two days.

27:50.480 --> 27:55.440
First, there was the strange letter. Then, the man with the black beard.

27:56.400 --> 28:03.280
Then, the missing brown shoe and the missing black shoe. Now, the return of the brown shoe.

28:04.160 --> 28:10.000
What did these things mean? Just before dinner, two telegrams arrived.

28:10.640 --> 28:16.320
One was from Sir Henry. Barrymore is at Baskerville Hall, not in London.

28:17.440 --> 28:24.720
The other was from Cartwright. I visited 23 hotels today. Sorry, no times.

28:26.240 --> 28:34.960
Oh, well, said Holmes. No luck there then, but I like difficult cases. Now, who's that at the door?

28:34.960 --> 28:43.680
A man came into the room. Good evening. I got your message. I'm the driver of cab 2704.

28:44.560 --> 28:51.120
Thank you for coming, said Holmes. I want to ask you some questions. What do you want to know?

28:52.800 --> 28:59.680
Tell me about your passenger this morning. He watched this house and then he followed two gentlemen.

29:00.480 --> 29:09.520
The cab driver was surprised. Yes, he did. He knew a lot already, but the gentleman was a detective.

29:10.160 --> 29:18.240
He told me his name. Holmes looked at me and smiled. Excellent. What was his name?

29:19.680 --> 29:25.200
His name, said the cab driver, was Mr. Sherlock Holmes.

29:26.080 --> 29:35.840
We were both very surprised, but Holmes continued, excellent again. Now, tell me, where did you go?

29:36.800 --> 29:43.360
He stopped me at half past nine in Trafalgar Square. Then we went to the Northumberland Hotel.

29:44.160 --> 29:51.280
Two gentlemen came out. They took a cab. We followed it. It stopped in Baker Street near here.

29:52.160 --> 29:57.600
We waited for about an hour and a half. Then they came out. We followed them.

29:58.640 --> 30:07.280
Then, suddenly in Regent Street, my passenger said, quick, take me to my hotel. So that's what I did.

30:08.640 --> 30:19.280
I see. And can you describe Mr. Sherlock Holmes? He was about 40 years old. He had a black beard and

30:19.280 --> 30:27.920
a pale face. He was quite tall, a bit like you, sir. Thank you very much. Here's some money for you.

30:29.520 --> 30:33.920
The cab driver went away. He looked very, very pleased.

30:35.360 --> 30:44.000
No luck there, either, said Holmes. Watson, this is a dangerous case. I'm worried about your visit

30:44.000 --> 30:50.720
to Dartmoor. I need you to go to Baskerville Hall, but you must be very careful.

30:52.960 --> 30:56.320
Chapter Three, The Prisoner on the More

30:58.560 --> 31:02.640
On Saturday, we met Baskerville and Mortimer at the station.

31:04.080 --> 31:08.560
Did you have a good week? Said Holmes. Did anyone follow you?

31:09.360 --> 31:13.120
No. No one followed us. Said Dr. Mortimer.

31:14.560 --> 31:21.360
And did you find your shoes, Henry? No, I didn't. Very interesting.

31:22.640 --> 31:28.720
Well, be careful at the hall and don't go on to the more alone at night.

31:30.080 --> 31:37.600
Holmes then looked at me. Right report to me, Watson, but I only want the facts.

31:38.320 --> 31:45.200
Tell me about Sir Henry's neighbours and about Sir Charles' death. Study the people on the more.

31:46.160 --> 31:55.440
Yes, of course. I see you've got your gun. Good. Always have it with you. Goodbye. And good luck, my friend.

31:57.600 --> 32:05.360
I got onto the train. It was a long journey, but I enjoyed it. I talked to Sir Henry and Dr.

32:05.360 --> 32:11.920
Mortimer, and I played with the doctor's friendly dog. Sir Henry looked out of the window.

32:12.720 --> 32:15.120
He was very interested in the countryside.

32:16.960 --> 32:22.560
I don't know what Baskerville Hall is like. I was only a teenager when my father died.

32:23.360 --> 32:28.240
We lived in a little house on the south coast, and I never visited the hall.

32:29.200 --> 32:34.400
Then, after my father died, I went to Canada. I can't wait to see the hall,

32:34.960 --> 32:36.880
and I can't wait to see the more.

32:38.160 --> 32:41.440
Well, there's the more, said Dr. Mortimer.

32:42.960 --> 32:52.240
Sir Henry looked out of the window. There was the more. He was silent. This was his new home.

32:52.240 --> 32:57.760
I saw he loved it. The train stopped at a small station.

32:58.720 --> 33:05.520
Outside the station, we saw a carriage with two horses. There were also two soldiers with guns.

33:06.560 --> 33:10.400
It was strange. Why were their soldiers here?

33:12.240 --> 33:16.000
Perkins, our driver, took us quickly to Baskerville Hall.

33:17.040 --> 33:23.120
Sir Henry asked lots of questions about the hall and the more. He was like a little boy

33:23.200 --> 33:29.520
excited about his new home. Then, in the distance, we saw a soldier on the hill.

33:30.480 --> 33:36.160
He was on a horse, and he had a gun. He watched our carriage as we passed.

33:37.680 --> 33:40.960
What's this about, Perkins? Said Dr. Mortimer.

33:41.920 --> 33:47.120
There's a prisoner on the moor. He escaped from Princeton Prison three days ago.

33:47.120 --> 33:52.240
The soldiers are watching all the roads and train stations. People are afraid, sir.

33:53.520 --> 33:59.440
Who is this prisoner? It's Selden, the Notting Hill Killer.

34:01.520 --> 34:06.800
Everyone in the carriage was silent. Then, at last, in the distance,

34:06.800 --> 34:10.720
we saw them, the two towers of Baskerville Hall.

34:12.480 --> 34:18.000
Sir Henry looked at the house. It doesn't look very friendly, he said.

34:18.880 --> 34:27.760
Then he smiled. I think it needs more light. Yes, electric light before next year. That's what we need.

34:29.520 --> 34:38.000
A tall man was at the door. A woman was with him. Welcome, Sir Henry. Welcome to Baskerville Hall.

34:40.160 --> 34:46.720
This was Barrymore, the butler, and his wife. They took our bags and we followed them inside.

34:48.000 --> 34:53.200
Well, Sir Henry, I must go. My wife's waiting. Said Dr. Mortimer.

34:54.080 --> 34:55.760
Have some dinner before you go.

34:56.640 --> 35:01.280
No, I must go home. But please call me anytime, night or day.

35:02.400 --> 35:08.560
Thank you, Dr. Mortimer. You're a good friend. Now, Barrymore, show us to our rooms.

35:08.560 --> 35:15.200
Is there any hot water? Can I have a wash? Yes, sir. There's hot water in your rooms.

35:16.160 --> 35:20.160
Thank you, Barrymore. But do you have something to say?

35:21.440 --> 35:29.440
Yes, sir. I'm sorry, but my wife and I want to leave here. We liked Sir Charles very much,

35:30.000 --> 35:35.440
and he gave us a lot of money in his will. The hall is a sad place for us now.

35:36.800 --> 35:43.280
Do you want to leave immediately? No, no. We can wait. Find a new butler first.

35:44.000 --> 35:48.160
Then we can leave. Can I show you your rooms now, sir?

35:50.000 --> 35:57.360
We followed Barrymore upstairs. My room was near Sir Henry's. It was almost next to it.

35:58.480 --> 36:06.720
These rooms were light and cheerful. The rest of the house was old and dark. I had a wash

36:06.720 --> 36:13.360
and changed my clothes for dinner. Then I went into the dining room where I met Sir Henry.

36:14.400 --> 36:22.080
It was a very large room, but it was also old and dark. Pictures of the Baskerville family were

36:22.080 --> 36:28.560
on the walls. They looked at us while we had our dinner. We both felt uncomfortable there.

36:29.360 --> 36:31.120
We didn't talk a lot at dinner.

36:31.920 --> 36:41.120
I'm not surprised my uncle was a nervous man, said Sir Henry. He was all alone in this big dark house.

36:42.320 --> 36:51.120
After dinner, we said good night and went to our rooms. I looked out of the window. I could

36:51.120 --> 36:59.920
see the garden in the moonlight. In the distance, there was the dark, lonely moor. I closed the

36:59.920 --> 37:06.640
curtains and went to bed. It was difficult to sleep. The house was silent.

37:08.080 --> 37:14.720
Then, suddenly in the middle of the night, I heard something. I sat up in bed and listened

37:14.720 --> 37:19.920
carefully. It wasn't far away, and it was certainly in the house.

37:20.480 --> 37:29.680
Someone's crying. I said to myself, it's a woman, and she's crying. Now, why?

37:33.280 --> 37:41.200
The next morning was beautiful. At breakfast, the sunlight filled the room. It was very different

37:41.200 --> 37:45.040
from the night before. We talked happily over breakfast.

37:45.600 --> 37:53.360
Perhaps we were tired last night. That's why this place looked sad. It was probably our imagination.

37:53.360 --> 38:03.680
Now it seems very cheerful. Yes, I answered. But did you hear anything last night? Did you hear a woman?

38:03.680 --> 38:12.880
Yes, I did. And she was very unhappy. She cried and cried. But I thought it was a dream.

38:13.760 --> 38:18.880
Well, it wasn't a dream. I heard it too.

38:21.280 --> 38:29.360
Sir Henry called Barrymore. He asked him about the woman. Barrymore's face went a little pale.

38:30.960 --> 38:37.360
There are only two women in the house, Sir Henry. One is the maid, and she sleeps in the other

38:37.360 --> 38:44.160
part of the house. The other woman is my wife. The sound did not come from her.

38:46.400 --> 38:54.400
But after breakfast, I met Mrs Barrymore. She looked unhappy, and her eyes were red.

38:55.680 --> 39:05.600
So she did cry in the night. But why? And why did her husband lie? Was he horrible to her?

39:06.480 --> 39:16.320
I was interested in Barrymore. He had a big black beard. He found Sir Charles's body.

39:17.520 --> 39:24.640
Was he the man in the cab? Did he follow Sir Henry and Dr Mortimer in London? I needed information.

39:25.760 --> 39:29.520
My first job was to talk to the man at Grimpen Post Office.

39:30.320 --> 39:35.840
Did he give the telegram to Barrymore and only Barrymore?

39:38.160 --> 39:45.600
After breakfast, I walked to the village. It was four miles away. The man at the post office

39:45.600 --> 39:53.600
remembered the telegram very well. My boy, James delivered it, didn't you, son? Yes, father, I did.

39:54.560 --> 40:03.040
And did you give it to Mr Barrymore himself? I asked. Well, he was upstairs, so I gave it to his wife.

40:04.480 --> 40:10.400
Did you see Mr Barrymore? No, sir. I said he was upstairs.

40:12.160 --> 40:16.720
You didn't see him, so how do you know he was upstairs?

40:17.600 --> 40:27.120
What's the problem? Said the boy's father. Mr Barrymore got the telegram. Why are you asking about Mr Barrymore's telegram?

40:27.680 --> 40:29.920
Why didn't he come here to ask about it?

40:32.000 --> 40:39.520
I saw that my investigation was at an end. I walked back along the grey lonely road and I thought.

40:40.320 --> 40:47.200
Perhaps Barrymore was our man in the cab. Was he at Baskerville Hall that day?

40:48.000 --> 40:51.760
According to his wife, he was. But was that true?

40:53.360 --> 41:00.960
Perhaps Barrymore killed Sir Charles. But why? And why did he follow Sir Henry?

41:02.240 --> 41:08.000
Why didn't he want Sir Henry at the hall? I thought about the strange message with the letters

41:08.080 --> 41:12.960
from the Times. Holmes was right. This was a very difficult case.

41:14.160 --> 41:20.640
Then suddenly I heard a voice behind me. I turned and I was surprised to see a stranger.

41:21.600 --> 41:30.960
He was small and thin. He had fair hair. He was about 30 or 40 years old. He had a grey suit

41:30.960 --> 41:37.600
and he had a hat on his head. He also had a butterfly net and a box for his specimens.

41:38.640 --> 41:44.640
You must be Dr Watson, he said. My name's Jack Stapleton. I live at Mary Pitt House.

41:45.680 --> 41:52.560
Please to meet you, I said. You're a naturalist, aren't you? But how did you know my name?

41:53.760 --> 41:59.440
I was at Dr Mortimer's house a moment ago. We saw you pass and he told me your name.

42:00.320 --> 42:07.040
I hope that Sir Henry is well after his journey. Yes, he's very well, thank you.

42:08.000 --> 42:14.080
I'm happy that he's here at Baskerville Hall. Do you know the story of the Baskerville Hound?

42:15.280 --> 42:21.280
Yes, I do. But Sir Henry doesn't believe in the supernatural. He isn't superstitious.

42:22.560 --> 42:28.720
A lot of people around here believe in the Hound. They say they can hear it at night too.

42:30.160 --> 42:37.360
He smiled, but I saw that he was worried. I'm sure that it was the reason for Sir Charles's death.

42:38.080 --> 42:45.600
He was a nervous man and he had a bad heart. Sir Charles believed the curse. But perhaps he

42:45.600 --> 42:54.400
really did see something that night on the path. I don't know. I was very sad about his death.

42:55.200 --> 43:02.000
I liked him very much. So did a dog chase him? Did he die of fright?

43:03.200 --> 43:09.920
I can't think of another reason, can you? At the moment, I haven't got any ideas at all.

43:10.960 --> 43:18.560
And what about Mr Holmes? Has he got any ideas? I was surprised to hear Holmes' name.

43:19.520 --> 43:27.600
Oh, we all know about the famous Sherlock Holmes. So, of course, we all know your name too.

43:28.560 --> 43:33.200
When Dr Mortimer told me your name, I immediately knew it was you.

43:34.160 --> 43:38.640
The fact that you're here means that Mr Holmes is interested in the case.

43:39.520 --> 43:45.760
What does he think about it? I'm sorry. I can't answer that question at the moment.

43:46.560 --> 43:52.640
Does he plan to visit us? He can't leave London. He's working on another case.

43:53.840 --> 43:59.920
What about your investigations? Do you need any help? Please ask me anytime.

44:01.120 --> 44:06.080
I'm here as a friend to Sir Henry. That's all. I don't need any help.

44:07.200 --> 44:14.960
Excellent, said Stapleton. You're right. You must be careful. I'm sorry I asked so many questions.

44:16.640 --> 44:22.080
We reached a small path in the road. I could see a house in the distance.

44:22.880 --> 44:27.120
That's Mary Pit House, he said. Come and meet my sister.

44:28.880 --> 44:33.120
I was pleased. It was a good opportunity to study the neighbours.

44:35.120 --> 44:42.080
It's a beautiful place, the more. I know it well. We only came here two years ago,

44:42.080 --> 44:48.080
just after Sir Charles came. I love walking, so I know them all very well.

44:49.280 --> 44:54.640
The houses over there are prehistoric, Neolithic man lived in them.

44:55.440 --> 45:03.920
And look there. That's the great Grimpen Maya. It looks green and friendly, but it's a terrible

45:03.920 --> 45:11.360
place. It's dangerous when the weather is dry. Now, after the autumn rain, it's almost impossible

45:11.360 --> 45:19.280
to cross it. Every year, people die drying. Every year, 10 or 20 horses die there too.

45:20.160 --> 45:28.320
The poor animals don't understand, but I can go to the very centre of the Maya and return alive.

45:30.000 --> 45:36.880
But why do you want to go to a horrible place like that? Why does anyone? Because it's full of

45:36.960 --> 45:45.520
rare plants and butterflies. How interesting. I like butterflies a lot. Perhaps I can go one day.

45:46.880 --> 45:53.520
Don't be a fool. It's too dangerous. I can get there because I remember some of the rocks and

45:53.520 --> 46:05.440
plants. It's too dangerous for you. Suddenly, we heard the low howl of a dog. It was long and sad.

46:06.960 --> 46:15.280
What's that? I said. The moors are strange place. People say it's the hound of the

46:15.280 --> 46:20.720
Baskavilles. I sometimes hear that sound when I walk out here.

46:23.360 --> 46:26.960
Chapter 4. The Hound of the Baskavilles

46:29.600 --> 46:32.960
I didn't believe the curse of the hound of the Baskavilles,

46:33.760 --> 46:39.600
but, Stapleton, what was that terrible howl on the moor? I asked again.

46:40.560 --> 46:45.520
You're an educated man. You don't believe those stories about the hound.

46:46.320 --> 46:50.240
What could the sound be? What makes a sound like that?

46:51.600 --> 46:58.320
Well, there's a very rare bird. It's called a biton. It makes a very strange sound. That's

46:58.400 --> 47:06.000
possible. Oh, just a moment. What's that? Excuse me, Dr. Watson. I must go. That butterfly.

47:06.000 --> 47:15.360
It's a cyclopides. He ran after the butterfly towards the grimp and mire. Stapleton ran and

47:15.360 --> 47:21.600
jumped, and I watched him get to the island in the centre. He knew the mire very well.

47:22.400 --> 47:29.040
Just then, I heard a person behind me. I turned and saw a woman.

47:30.320 --> 47:34.800
Go back, she said. Go back to London immediately.

47:36.000 --> 47:39.920
But why? I asked. I was very surprised.

47:41.040 --> 47:48.800
I can't explain. Please go back to London. Don't come here again. Now, quiet. My brother's coming.

47:49.600 --> 47:57.440
Hello, Beryl. He said. But I didn't think he was very happy to see his sister.

47:58.720 --> 48:06.960
Hello, Jack. You're very hot, said Miss Stapleton. Yes, I saw a cyclopides and I chased it.

48:08.240 --> 48:14.320
He looked at us both. I see. Now you know, Dr. Watson.

48:14.320 --> 48:22.480
Are you Dr. Watson? Sherlock Holmes, his friend. But I thought you were Sir Henry Baskerville.

48:23.840 --> 48:25.280
She looked a little worried.

48:28.240 --> 48:34.880
We walked to Mary Pit House. It looked dark and sad. We went inside.

48:35.920 --> 48:40.800
I looked out of the window. The only view was of the lonely mall.

48:41.600 --> 48:46.720
Why do they live here? I thought. It's a sad, dark place.

48:48.800 --> 48:52.480
It's a strange place to live, isn't it? Said Stapleton.

48:53.200 --> 48:59.840
I had a school in the north of England. Unfortunately, one winter, some of the boys became ill.

49:00.640 --> 49:07.920
Three of them died. The school closed. I didn't have a lot of money, but I had the money to buy

49:08.000 --> 49:15.040
this place. I like it here. Dartmoor's a good place for my hobby, and my sister likes it here too.

49:15.920 --> 49:20.880
We have our books and we have our studies, and we have our interesting neighbours.

49:21.760 --> 49:26.880
That's right. Isn't it, Beryl? Oh, yes, she said quickly.

49:28.560 --> 49:36.240
Dr. Mortimer is an interesting man. Poor Sir Charles was also a good friend. We knew him well,

49:36.240 --> 49:40.320
and we miss him. I would like to meet Sir Henry, his nephew.

49:41.760 --> 49:46.000
Come to the hall this afternoon, I said. You can meet him then.

49:48.240 --> 49:56.800
I said goodbye and walked across the mall. After about five minutes, I was very surprised to see

49:56.800 --> 50:05.280
Miss Stapleton in front of me. I must be quick, she said. Don't tell my brother. Please forget

50:05.280 --> 50:08.800
everything that I said to you. I thought you were Sir Henry.

50:10.400 --> 50:14.960
I can't forget it. And why must Sir Henry go back to London?

50:16.400 --> 50:21.280
The curse of the Hound. Sir Henry is in danger. Now I must go.

50:23.120 --> 50:32.880
She walked away. I went back to Baskerville Hall. I was worried. I wrote my report to Holmes.

50:35.280 --> 50:42.560
Now I plan to use my reports to Holmes and my diary. They give the reader a complete account of

50:42.560 --> 50:53.360
events. Baskerville Hall October 13th. Dear Holmes, I told you about the prisoner in my last report.

50:54.160 --> 51:02.000
Now I've got more news. The prisoner escaped two weeks ago. Nobody knows where he is.

51:02.960 --> 51:06.960
Where is he finding food? Is he still on the mall?

51:08.160 --> 51:13.120
I'm worried about the Stapleton's in their lonely house. Sir Henry is worried too.

51:13.920 --> 51:19.840
He asked Perkins the driver to sleep at their house. Mr Stapleton said no.

51:21.440 --> 51:29.200
I think Sir Henry likes Miss Stapleton very much. She's a beautiful woman. Almost a warm,

51:29.280 --> 51:36.960
Latin beauty. It's strange that her brother is so cold. He's got a lot of power over her.

51:37.840 --> 51:43.680
She looks at him all the time. She wants to please him. I hope he's kind to her.

51:44.400 --> 51:49.840
He sometimes looks quite hard. Anyway, here are the facts.

51:51.920 --> 51:58.160
Stapleton came to the hall on that first day. The next morning, he showed us the place where

51:58.160 --> 52:06.960
the evil Sir Hugo died in 1647. It was a horrible, lonely place. Sir Henry didn't like it.

52:08.000 --> 52:13.840
Stapleton clearly believes this horrible curse. He believes there's a hound on the mall.

52:15.840 --> 52:22.000
We had lunch at Mary Pit House. Sir Henry met Miss Stapleton for the first time.

52:22.800 --> 52:29.920
They liked each other. Now they see each other every day. They have an invitation for dinner

52:29.920 --> 52:38.400
at the hall tonight. We have an invitation to go there next week. It's strange. But Mr Stapleton

52:38.400 --> 52:44.480
doesn't seem very happy about this. He looks angry when Sir Henry talks to his sister.

52:45.440 --> 52:53.200
Perhaps he can see a lonely life in the future without her. But I think he's selfish to think that.

52:55.280 --> 53:02.800
I also met another neighbour the other day, Mr Franklin of Laughter Hall. He's an interesting

53:02.800 --> 53:10.160
old man with a red face. He likes the stars and the night sky. There's a telescope on the roof of

53:10.240 --> 53:14.240
his house. At the moment, he's looking for the prisoner with it.

53:16.000 --> 53:24.160
Now, I must tell you about the Barrymore's. I told you about the telegram. Was Barrymore

53:24.160 --> 53:32.800
the butler in London that day or was he here? We don't know. Sir Henry decided to ask him about

53:32.800 --> 53:41.840
it. He asked lots of questions. He seemed quite hard with Barrymore. Later in the evening,

53:41.840 --> 53:48.560
Barrymore spoke to Sir Henry. Barrymore doesn't understand why Sir Henry is suspicious.

53:49.760 --> 53:57.520
After this, Sir Henry felt sorry for Barrymore. The next morning, he gave some of his old clothes

53:57.520 --> 54:00.720
to Barrymore. The butler was very pleased.

54:02.640 --> 54:11.040
I'm interested in Mrs Barrymore too. She cries a lot. Is Barrymore a violent man?

54:12.960 --> 54:22.800
Then, last night, I woke up suddenly. Someone was outside my room. I looked out. There was a man

54:22.800 --> 54:32.240
at the end of the corridor. It was Barrymore. He walked very quietly. He didn't have any shoes

54:32.240 --> 54:42.080
on. I followed him. He went into one of the empty rooms. The door was open. I could see the light

54:42.080 --> 54:50.640
from his candle. I looked into the room. Barrymore was at the window with his candle. He watched for

54:50.640 --> 54:58.080
a long time. Then, suddenly, he turned, but he didn't see me. I ran back to my room.

54:58.960 --> 55:06.000
A few minutes later, he passed my door. You only want the facts, Holmes. So there they are.

55:08.720 --> 55:11.360
Baskerville Hall October 15th.

55:12.720 --> 55:15.280
Dear Holmes, here is my next report.

55:15.280 --> 55:23.680
The next morning, I went to the room at the end of the corridor. Its window has an excellent

55:23.680 --> 55:30.800
view of the more. I'm sure that Barrymore is interested in something or someone out there.

55:31.840 --> 55:39.520
After breakfast, I told Sir Henry about it. He wasn't surprised. Sir Henry also hears Barrymore

55:39.520 --> 55:42.880
at night. We're planning to follow him tonight.

55:44.400 --> 55:51.440
After our conversation, Sir Henry decided to go out. I wanted to go with him. He wanted

55:51.440 --> 55:59.840
to go alone. He wanted to meet Miss Stapleton. This was a difficult problem. My instructions

55:59.840 --> 56:07.280
from you are clear, Holmes. I can't leave him alone. But I understood his reasons. He clearly

56:07.280 --> 56:13.680
wanted to be alone with her. I decided to follow him, but at a distance.

56:14.880 --> 56:21.520
I walked quickly towards Merippitt House. At first, I couldn't see Sir Henry at all,

56:21.520 --> 56:30.400
so I climbed a hill. Then, I saw him with Miss Stapleton. Sir Henry tried to kiss Miss Stapleton.

56:30.480 --> 56:37.520
She didn't want him to. Then, I saw another person on the moor. It was Mr Stapleton

56:37.520 --> 56:44.640
with his green butterfly net. He ran towards them and shouted. He seemed angry with them.

56:45.680 --> 56:49.120
Then, he walked away, and his sister followed him.

56:50.400 --> 56:54.560
Sir Henry walked towards the hall. He looked very sad.

56:55.040 --> 57:01.120
I was sorry for Sir Henry, so I went down the hill to meet him.

57:02.160 --> 57:07.920
He was confused about Stapleton. Sir Henry wants to marry Miss Stapleton,

57:07.920 --> 57:15.200
and he can't understand her brother's behaviour. Stapleton says he's sorry and that he's selfish.

57:15.840 --> 57:21.440
He doesn't want his life to change. He asked Sir Henry to wait for three months

57:21.440 --> 57:23.760
before asking Miss Stapleton to marry him.

57:25.360 --> 57:28.640
Now, Holmes, let me tell you about Barrymore.

57:30.160 --> 57:37.920
The first night, we waited in Sir Henry's room until three o'clock. Nothing. We tried again last

57:37.920 --> 57:45.760
night. Just after two o'clock, we heard someone in the corridor. It was Barrymore. He went into

57:45.760 --> 57:52.720
the empty room. We looked in. There he was, with his candle and the window again.

57:53.920 --> 58:01.120
Sir Henry walked into the room. Barrymore went pale. Sir Henry asked Barrymore to explain,

58:01.840 --> 58:08.560
but Barrymore was silent. I took the candle from Barrymore and moved it in front of the window.

58:09.520 --> 58:16.000
After a few seconds, I saw a light on the moor. Someone answered my signal.

58:17.440 --> 58:25.360
Suddenly, we heard a woman's voice and Mrs. Barrymore came into the room. She explained everything.

58:26.720 --> 58:31.920
The man on the moor is her brother, Selden, the escaped prisoner.

58:33.280 --> 58:38.080
She can't leave her brother alone on the moor without help. He needs food.

58:39.280 --> 58:42.800
He shows a light, and Barrymore takes the food to him.

58:45.040 --> 58:53.680
Sir Henry and I decided to get Selden. I got my gun and we went out onto the moor towards the light.

58:55.280 --> 59:01.360
Suddenly, we heard it again. That long, low, horrible howl.

59:02.240 --> 59:10.800
Sir Henry seemed a little afraid. He thought the howl came from the Grimpen mire. He was probably right.

59:11.920 --> 59:17.920
I think Sir Henry was afraid because of the curse. I think he remembered that there were

59:17.920 --> 59:25.120
a hound's footprints next to his uncle's body. We went on in the dark towards the light.

59:26.080 --> 59:29.520
Finally, we arrived, but there wasn't anyone there.

59:30.720 --> 59:37.680
Then we saw Selden in the moonlight. We ran towards him, but he was fast and we couldn't catch him.

59:38.720 --> 59:45.600
He escaped. We turned to go home. Then, a strange thing happened.

59:47.040 --> 59:52.800
On a hill, in front of us in the moonlight, I saw a tall stranger.

59:53.440 --> 01:00:01.840
The man saw us and went away. I wanted to follow him, but Sir Henry was very tired. We went home.

01:00:03.440 --> 01:00:08.160
This morning, we told the soldiers. I hope they can find Selden.

01:00:09.600 --> 01:00:13.360
Finish your case quickly, Holmes. We need you here.

01:00:13.360 --> 01:00:19.040
Diary entry October 16.

01:00:20.800 --> 01:00:30.240
It's a wet, foggy day. Sir Henry seems very unhappy. I'm also worried. I think this place is dangerous.

01:00:31.200 --> 01:00:37.760
I don't believe the story is about the hound. I'm not superstitious like Stapleton or Mortimer.

01:00:38.640 --> 01:00:44.560
People here say it's a horrible thing to see. I don't think the stories are true,

01:00:45.200 --> 01:00:51.280
but I know there's something out there. It howls like a hound, but where is it?

01:00:52.240 --> 01:00:57.600
Where can a gigantic dog live on the moor? Where does it find food?

01:00:59.360 --> 01:01:05.200
What about the man on the hill last night? Is he the man we saw in London?

01:01:06.160 --> 01:01:13.360
A stranger is still following us. I must find out about him. I need an answer to this problem,

01:01:13.360 --> 01:01:16.160
but I don't want to tell Sir Henry about it.

01:01:17.920 --> 01:01:23.360
This morning Barrymore came to talk to us. He had some important information.

01:01:24.400 --> 01:01:32.160
He knew why Sir Charles went to the gate the night he died. Sir Charles had a letter from a woman.

01:01:33.040 --> 01:01:38.800
He went to meet her. Mrs Barrymore found a piece of the letter in the fireplace.

01:01:40.000 --> 01:01:45.600
It was still possible to read the end of the letter. It was a woman's writing,

01:01:45.600 --> 01:01:51.600
and it said, Be at the gate at ten o'clock. Burn this letter.

01:01:53.120 --> 01:01:56.720
At the bottom were the letters L-L.

01:01:56.720 --> 01:02:01.520
Chapter 5 The Man on the Hill

01:02:03.200 --> 01:02:06.080
Diary entry October 17.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:15.120
It rained all day again today. I thought about the prisoner on the moor. Poor man.

01:02:16.320 --> 01:02:22.880
Then I thought about the stranger on the hill. He was on the moor in this horrible weather too.

01:02:23.840 --> 01:02:26.080
Why? Who was he?

01:02:27.680 --> 01:02:33.920
In the evening I put on my coat and went back to the hill. There was no one there.

01:02:35.120 --> 01:02:42.240
As I walked back Dr Mortimer drove past me. He stopped and I got into his carriage.

01:02:43.360 --> 01:02:49.600
He's worried. His little dog is missing. He lost her on the moor yesterday.

01:02:50.560 --> 01:02:53.600
I'm sorry for him. I hope he finds her.

01:02:54.880 --> 01:03:01.920
I asked him about the letters L-L. He knows a woman in the town of Coom Tracy.

01:03:01.920 --> 01:03:08.640
She's called Laura Lyons. Perhaps she wrote the letter. She's Franklin's daughter.

01:03:10.000 --> 01:03:16.960
She married an artist called Lyons, but her father didn't like the man. Her father was right.

01:03:17.840 --> 01:03:25.680
Lyons was a horrible man. He left her. A lot of people here help her. They sometimes give her a

01:03:25.680 --> 01:03:35.760
little money. Sometimes Sir Charles gave her money too. After dinner I talked to Barrymore about

01:03:35.760 --> 01:03:43.840
Selden. Barrymore took food for him three days ago, but he didn't see Selden's signal last night

01:03:43.920 --> 01:03:48.080
or two nights ago. He doesn't know where Selden is now.

01:03:49.600 --> 01:03:56.640
Barrymore surprised me because he knows about the stranger on the moor too. Selden told him.

01:03:57.680 --> 01:04:06.880
The stranger lives in the prehistoric houses and a boy brings him food. Yes, I need to find out.

01:04:07.840 --> 01:04:12.320
Why is someone living on the moor in this terrible weather?

01:04:13.280 --> 01:04:21.120
The following morning I told Sir Henry about Laura Lyons and the letter. He was very interested

01:04:21.120 --> 01:04:26.800
and very surprised. She wanted to meet him at the moor gate at ten o'clock,

01:04:27.520 --> 01:04:33.600
but that's exactly where and when my uncle died, go to Coom Tracy, talk to this woman.

01:04:33.600 --> 01:04:43.760
I arrived in Coom Tracy and I asked about Laura Lyons. People there knew her and it was easy to

01:04:43.760 --> 01:04:50.400
find her house. She was surprised to see a stranger, but she asked me to come inside.

01:04:52.400 --> 01:04:56.560
I'm here because I want to talk about Charles Baskerville, I said.

01:04:56.560 --> 01:05:04.400
What can I tell you about him? He was a very kind man. He helped me a lot.

01:05:04.400 --> 01:05:13.680
Did you write to him? She looked a little angry. I wrote to him once or twice to say thank you.

01:05:13.680 --> 01:05:22.800
He gave me some money. He was very kind. Did you ask Sir Charles to meet you?

01:05:23.520 --> 01:05:29.200
I asked. Really, Sir? That's a very strange question. Of course I didn't.

01:05:30.080 --> 01:05:38.320
Oh, I think you did. In fact, you wrote to him on the day he died. You wanted to meet him

01:05:38.320 --> 01:05:50.160
at the moor gate at ten o'clock. She went pale. Yes. Yes. I did write a letter,

01:05:50.240 --> 01:05:58.800
but he burnt it. I know he did. How do you know about it? It was a private letter.

01:06:00.080 --> 01:06:04.960
A piece of the letter didn't burn. The letters L.L. were on it.

01:06:06.480 --> 01:06:09.840
Why did you want to meet him at that time and at that place?

01:06:11.760 --> 01:06:19.760
He had plans. He wanted to go to London on May 5th. I needed his help before he went

01:06:19.840 --> 01:06:25.360
to London. I was busy until ten o'clock that night. I had to meet him in the garden.

01:06:26.400 --> 01:06:33.360
A woman can't go into a single man's house at night. It's not correct. That's why I wanted

01:06:33.360 --> 01:06:44.080
to meet him by the gate. What did you do when you arrived? I didn't go. Before I went,

01:06:44.080 --> 01:06:52.000
someone came to see me. He gave me the help that I needed. But please, I can't tell you his name.

01:06:54.480 --> 01:07:01.920
Her story was probably true. But why did she go so pale? What did she want to hide?

01:07:03.680 --> 01:07:07.200
I said goodbye, and Perkins drove me towards the hall.

01:07:07.200 --> 01:07:17.680
On the way home, we saw Mr. Franklin in his garden. He invited me for a glass of wine. I sent Perkins home.

01:07:19.360 --> 01:07:26.320
Franklin was an interesting man. He talked about the more and about the stars. He showed me his

01:07:26.320 --> 01:07:34.800
telescope. I'm using this to watch the prisoner, he said. A young boy brings him food every day.

01:07:35.280 --> 01:07:37.680
Look, Watson. There he is now, on that hill.

01:07:39.600 --> 01:07:46.720
I looked over towards the hill. Yes. There was a boy there. He had a parcel with him.

01:07:47.680 --> 01:07:55.040
I saw him go towards the prehistoric houses. Now I knew where the stranger was. I decided to

01:07:55.040 --> 01:08:02.640
investigate. Well, I must go now, Mr. Franklin. Thank you for the wine. I enjoyed our interesting

01:08:02.720 --> 01:08:09.600
conversation, too. I walked up the hill and looked at the prehistoric houses.

01:08:10.720 --> 01:08:20.160
Only one had a roof. The man lived here, I was sure. I quietly went inside. It was empty.

01:08:21.200 --> 01:08:26.560
The parcel of food was on the floor, and there was a small place for a bed in the corner.

01:08:27.520 --> 01:08:36.640
I decided to wait for the stranger. I sat in the dark with my gun. I waited for a long time.

01:08:37.840 --> 01:08:46.800
Then I heard someone outside. I sat very quietly. Then I heard a voice.

01:08:47.680 --> 01:08:53.200
It's a beautiful evening, Watson. Why don't you come outside?

01:08:54.640 --> 01:09:05.040
Holmes, it's you. I ran outside. I'm so happy to see you. But how did you know it was me in here?

01:09:06.080 --> 01:09:11.040
You spoke to Cigarette over there. It says Brantley of Oxford Street on it.

01:09:12.000 --> 01:09:18.640
How many men on Dartmoor buy their cigarettes in Oxford Street? But how did you find me?

01:09:19.600 --> 01:09:23.920
I wasn't very careful that night on the hill. You saw me, I know.

01:09:24.960 --> 01:09:33.360
But how did you know which house I was in? It was your boy. I saw him. But why are you living like this?

01:09:34.640 --> 01:09:40.160
I'm investigating, but in secret. Cartwright's helping me. He's a very good boy.

01:09:41.040 --> 01:09:47.680
Now, Watson, what do you know? Tell me. I told Holmes about Laura Lyons.

01:09:49.280 --> 01:09:58.080
That's very interesting. I think Laura Lyons is in love with Stapleton. I also know that Miss

01:09:58.080 --> 01:10:06.800
Stapleton isn't Mr. Stapleton's sister. She's his wife. So that's why Mr. Stapleton was angry

01:10:06.800 --> 01:10:12.720
with St Henry that day. But why? Why are they pretending to be brother and sister?

01:10:14.320 --> 01:10:21.360
He doesn't want people to know he's married. Stapleton's our man, Watson. Stapleton's our killer,

01:10:21.360 --> 01:10:29.680
I'm sure. But are you sure she's his wife? Yes. Do you remember your first conversation?

01:10:30.640 --> 01:10:36.160
He told you about his school in the north of England. A lot of the things he said do you

01:10:36.160 --> 01:10:43.840
are false. But these were true. Yes. He's interested in butterflies and he was once a teacher.

01:10:44.960 --> 01:10:54.880
Yes, three boys died at his school. With those facts, it was easy. I found the school. After that,

01:10:54.880 --> 01:11:04.480
the rest was easy too. But he's married. What about poor Laura Lyons? Yes, poor woman.

01:11:05.360 --> 01:11:11.840
She wants a divorce from her husband. I think she wants to marry Stapleton and she needs his

01:11:11.840 --> 01:11:19.120
help with money. She doesn't know he's already married. We need to talk to her again. We need

01:11:19.120 --> 01:11:25.760
to tell her. Now, Watson, let's go up to the hall. Baskerville is alone there and I don't like it.

01:11:26.480 --> 01:11:29.600
Stapleton's a killer, Watson. A killer.

01:11:30.400 --> 01:11:40.000
Suddenly, in the darkness, there was a terrible, low howl and it came from the mall. The hound,

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:48.880
cried Holmes. Oh no, Stapleton's out there. Then we heard a terrible scream. He's got Sir Henry.

01:11:48.880 --> 01:11:56.720
Holmes quickly ran in the direction of the scream. I ran behind him. We stopped at the bottom of the hill,

01:11:57.280 --> 01:12:05.920
but we couldn't see anything. Then I saw it. It was a man's body. He was faced down on the ground.

01:12:06.880 --> 01:12:13.440
He was dead. Holmes lit a match. And in the light, we saw the dead man's jacket.

01:12:14.480 --> 01:12:18.640
It was Sir Henry's jacket. The dead man was Sir Henry.

01:12:19.600 --> 01:12:28.560
Oh no. Why did I leave Sir Henry alone today? Oh, why did I go to Coombe Tracy? Why did Sir Henry go

01:12:28.560 --> 01:12:38.240
on to the mall alone? Holmes went over to Sir Henry's body. He turned it over. Then he shouted.

01:12:39.440 --> 01:12:45.920
He's got a beard. This isn't Sir Henry. This is the prisoner Selden. Sir Henry is alive.

01:12:46.720 --> 01:12:54.000
Of course. Sir Henry gave some clothes to Barrymore. Barrymore probably gave them to Selden.

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:56.640
That's why Selden's wearing Sir Henry's jacket.

01:12:57.520 --> 01:13:05.120
Hello. Who's this? Said Holmes. Someone's coming. It's probably Stapleton. Be careful.

01:13:06.640 --> 01:13:11.840
Stapleton arrived and looked at the body. Who's that? He said.

01:13:12.720 --> 01:13:19.600
It's Selden, the prisoner from Prince Town. Stapleton's face was pale.

01:13:21.360 --> 01:13:30.880
How horrible is he dead? Yes. He probably broke his neck. We were on the hill over there and we

01:13:30.880 --> 01:13:38.800
heard a scream. We ran down here and found him. I heard a scream too. That's why I'm here.

01:13:39.440 --> 01:13:44.880
I was worried about Sir Henry. I invited him to my house tonight, but he didn't come.

01:13:45.840 --> 01:13:55.840
Did you hear any other sounds? No. Why? Oh, you know, people talk about the hound on the more.

01:13:57.040 --> 01:14:04.800
What do you think, Mr. Holmes? I'm right, aren't I? You are Sherlock Holmes. Well, what do you think?

01:14:05.680 --> 01:14:16.800
Yes, you're right. But no, we didn't hear anything. We found this poor man here. I think he fell and broke his neck.

01:14:17.760 --> 01:14:22.000
That's what I think. Stapleton relaxed.

01:14:23.360 --> 01:14:28.880
I'm happy you're here, he said. Now you can help Dr. Watson with this problem.

01:14:29.760 --> 01:14:36.800
I'm sorry, I can't, said Holmes. I still have a case in London. I need to go back there.

01:14:38.560 --> 01:14:45.760
We covered the body. Stapleton went back to Merippet House and Holmes and I went back to the hall.

01:14:48.240 --> 01:14:55.600
We are near to the end now, said Holmes. Did you see Stapleton's face? He was very shocked

01:14:55.680 --> 01:15:02.560
when he saw Selden. I'm sorry, he knows I'm here, but there's nothing we can do. Now,

01:15:03.440 --> 01:15:10.640
how can we catch him, Watson? How? Let's talk to the police tonight. We know he's our man.

01:15:11.440 --> 01:15:20.000
Proof, Watson. We need proof. All we have is a body and a dog. There's no connection with Stapleton.

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:29.680
The police need proof. But there's Sir Charles's death. Yes, but again we need proof. You and I

01:15:29.680 --> 01:15:36.080
know that he died of fright, but where's the proof? No, Watson. We must wait.

01:15:37.520 --> 01:15:42.640
Just one more thing, said Holmes. When we arrive at Baskerville Hall,

01:15:43.280 --> 01:15:50.160
don't tell Sir Henry about the Hound. Sir Henry was pleased to see Holmes,

01:15:50.720 --> 01:15:59.440
but my first job was to see Barrymore and his wife. I told them about Selden. Mrs. Barrymore

01:15:59.440 --> 01:16:08.640
cried and cried. To her, he wasn't a horrible man. He was her little brother. I was sorry for her.

01:16:09.520 --> 01:16:15.040
Then we told Sir Henry about Selden, but we didn't talk about the Hound.

01:16:16.800 --> 01:16:23.680
I stayed in the house all morning, said Sir Henry. It was very boring. I got a message from

01:16:23.680 --> 01:16:29.680
Stapleton. He invited me to dinner tonight, but I did as you asked. I didn't go out.

01:16:29.680 --> 01:16:40.160
Selden had your jacket, said Holmes. We thought you were dead. It was a terrible shock. I imagined

01:16:40.160 --> 01:16:50.160
Barrymore gave it to Selden. Yes, probably, said Sir Henry. Now Holmes, have you got any news for us?

01:16:52.080 --> 01:16:55.440
Things are going well. I think we're near the end.

01:16:56.320 --> 01:17:04.480
It was very late, but we went into the dining room for dinner. Holmes looked at the paintings on the wall.

01:17:05.520 --> 01:17:16.800
He smiled. Yes, things are going very well. These pictures are very interesting. I think some of them

01:17:16.800 --> 01:17:24.720
are very good. That's a Reynolds, and this one here is a Nella. Are they all family portraits?

01:17:26.320 --> 01:17:33.680
Yes, they are, said Sir Henry. Barrymore's teaching me all their names. This is Sir William

01:17:33.680 --> 01:17:40.480
Baskerville. He was a politician. This is Admiral Baskerville. He went to the West Indies.

01:17:42.000 --> 01:17:49.680
What about this one here? That's the evil Sir Hugo. It's strange because he doesn't look evil,

01:17:50.480 --> 01:17:53.600
but the date is on the back, 1647.

01:17:56.000 --> 01:18:02.640
After dinner, Sir Henry went to his room. Holmes looked again at the picture of Sir Hugo.

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:05.280
Do you see it, Watson?

01:18:07.360 --> 01:18:13.600
I looked at the man with a large hat. He had long, curly hair, and a thin face.

01:18:13.840 --> 01:18:25.760
He looks a little bit like Sir Henry, I said. Holmes got onto a chair. He put his hands over the hat and the long hair.

01:18:27.520 --> 01:18:34.160
Suddenly, I saw it. Stapleton. Stapleton is a Baskerville.

01:18:34.400 --> 01:18:39.680
Our first piece of proof was there on the wall.

01:18:41.200 --> 01:18:44.080
Chapter 6 – Catching the Killer

01:18:45.760 --> 01:18:49.680
The next morning, Holmes told the police about Selden's body.

01:18:50.480 --> 01:18:53.520
Then, at breakfast, he told us his plan.

01:18:55.120 --> 01:19:02.640
Today is a big day for all of us, but I need your help, Sir Henry. This is very, very important.

01:19:03.280 --> 01:19:09.040
You must do what I say, but you mustn't ask any questions. Can you do that?

01:19:10.400 --> 01:19:12.480
Yes, I can. Good.

01:19:14.000 --> 01:19:18.400
You've got an invitation for dinner with the Stapleton's tonight. Is that right?

01:19:19.600 --> 01:19:23.200
Yes, and Watson's coming. Do you want to come too?

01:19:24.400 --> 01:19:27.680
No, I'm sorry. Watson and I must go to London.

01:19:28.320 --> 01:19:30.640
Sir Henry looked worried.

01:19:32.080 --> 01:19:35.120
But these days, I don't like being alone here.

01:19:36.480 --> 01:19:43.360
Trust me. Go to dinner with the Stapleton's. Tell them that we're very sorry, but we've got

01:19:43.360 --> 01:19:50.080
important business in London. Please give them that message. When you arrive at Mary Pit House,

01:19:50.640 --> 01:19:55.840
send Perkins home. Tell the Stapleton's that you want to walk home.

01:19:56.640 --> 01:20:00.240
Walk across the moor at night alone.

01:20:01.200 --> 01:20:06.560
Yes, but don't worry. Go straight to the hall. Stay on the path.

01:20:08.560 --> 01:20:14.560
We said goodbye to Sir Henry. Perkins took us to the station, then went home to the hall.

01:20:15.680 --> 01:20:20.720
Young Cartwright was at the station. There's a telegram for you, sir.

01:20:21.840 --> 01:20:22.880
Thank you, Gardwright.

01:20:23.680 --> 01:20:30.160
Holmes looked at the message. It said, arrive 540. Lestrade.

01:20:31.520 --> 01:20:37.840
Good. It's from Detective Lestrade. Now, Stapleton needs proof we're in London.

01:20:38.400 --> 01:20:43.680
He mustn't think we're here. Cartwright takes the train to London. When you arrive,

01:20:44.240 --> 01:20:46.560
send this telegram to Sir Henry.

01:20:46.560 --> 01:20:59.120
I left my diary in my room. I need it urgently. Send it to me at Baker Street as soon as possible.

01:21:00.000 --> 01:21:10.320
Holmes. Do you understand? Yes, sir. Watson, come with me. I want to talk to Laura Lyons.

01:21:11.200 --> 01:21:18.640
Mrs. Lyons was surprised to see us. There are some facts missing from your story, Mrs. Lyons.

01:21:18.640 --> 01:21:26.720
We need more information, said Holmes. I told your friend everything. Not everything.

01:21:27.680 --> 01:21:33.360
You asked Sir Charles to meet you at the gate at 10 o'clock, the time and place of his death.

01:21:34.560 --> 01:21:38.400
What's the connection? There isn't a connection.

01:21:38.640 --> 01:21:46.720
This is a case of murder, Mrs. Lyons. The case involves your friend, Mr. Stapleton, and his wife.

01:21:46.720 --> 01:21:56.080
His wife? But Mr. Stapleton's single. He lives with his sister. I'm sorry. But that's not true.

01:21:56.080 --> 01:22:02.960
She's really his wife. Here's a photograph of them from four years ago. On the back, it says,

01:22:03.120 --> 01:22:10.480
Mr. and Mrs. Vandellur. But you can see the people in the picture are the Stapleton's.

01:22:11.920 --> 01:22:21.120
Poor Laura Lyons was very shocked. Mr. Holmes, this man asked me to marry him. He lied to me.

01:22:21.920 --> 01:22:27.440
He told me to write that letter. He is an evil man. Ask me anything you want.

01:22:27.520 --> 01:22:35.120
Did Stapleton dictate that letter? Yes, every word of it. With Sir Charles's money,

01:22:35.120 --> 01:22:42.400
he said a divorce from my husband was possible. Then he could marry me. I believed him.

01:22:42.400 --> 01:22:50.160
After I wrote the letter, he told me not to go to Baskerville Hall. He told me not to meet Sir Charles.

01:22:50.160 --> 01:22:55.600
He wanted to give me the money himself. He didn't want Sir Charles to give me money.

01:22:56.240 --> 01:23:02.400
Then, the next day, you read about Sir Charles's death in the newspaper. Is that right?

01:23:02.400 --> 01:23:11.600
Yes. Stapleton told me not to say anything about the letter. He said it looked bad for me. After that,

01:23:11.600 --> 01:23:19.200
I didn't trust him. You're very lucky. Stapleton's an evil man.

01:23:20.160 --> 01:23:30.640
Later, Holmes and I went back to the station. The London train arrived and a small, strong-looking man got off the train.

01:23:31.680 --> 01:23:32.880
He walked towards us.

01:23:34.320 --> 01:23:36.080
Anything good? He said.

01:23:37.360 --> 01:23:42.160
Very, very good, Lestrade said Holmes. Let's talk about it over dinner.

01:23:42.880 --> 01:23:52.320
Holmes told Lestrade the whole story, but he didn't talk about his plans. Finally, I asked about them.

01:23:52.320 --> 01:23:58.560
What are your plans? We need to know Holmes. We need to know what to do.

01:23:58.560 --> 01:24:03.760
Don't worry. Trust me, he said.

01:24:04.240 --> 01:24:14.480
After dinner, we took a cab towards Meripit House. When we arrived, Holmes finally gave us some instructions.

01:24:14.480 --> 01:24:17.840
We were about 200 yards from the house.

01:24:19.520 --> 01:24:29.680
Be very quiet. Walk on Tiptoe. Let's hide here. Now, Watson, you know this house. There's a light in those

01:24:29.680 --> 01:24:36.560
windows there. What's that room? That's the kitchen. And the windows there are the dining room.

01:24:37.600 --> 01:24:45.760
Good. The curtains are open. Go quietly. Look inside. Tell us what you see.

01:24:48.080 --> 01:24:53.840
I walked down the path very quietly. I looked in through the dining room window.

01:24:54.640 --> 01:25:03.840
There were two men inside, Stapleton and Sir Henry. Stapleton's wife wasn't there. I watched them.

01:25:05.200 --> 01:25:12.400
Then Stapleton went out of the room. Henry sat down. He looked very pale.

01:25:14.000 --> 01:25:20.240
I heard a door open and the sound of shoes on the path. It was Stapleton.

01:25:21.120 --> 01:25:29.360
He went into a small building near the house. I heard some sounds inside. Then he came out again.

01:25:30.480 --> 01:25:37.840
He was only in the building for a minute. I quickly went back to Holmes and the straight. I told them about it.

01:25:39.280 --> 01:25:46.480
But where's Stapleton's wife? Said Holmes. There are only two lights in the house. One in the kitchen,

01:25:47.040 --> 01:25:50.880
but only the servants are in there. The other is in the dining room.

01:25:51.680 --> 01:25:56.640
Only Sir Henry and Stapleton are in there. Where is she?

01:25:57.840 --> 01:26:07.120
I don't know. I said. But look. Look at the grimp and mire. The fog's coming and it's coming towards us.

01:26:07.120 --> 01:26:15.520
It's moving very quickly. This is bad, Watson. I don't like it. The fog is the only thing which

01:26:15.520 --> 01:26:20.800
can stop our plan. Then Holmes said almost to himself,

01:26:21.920 --> 01:26:26.080
come away from Meribith House, Sir Henry. Come out soon.

01:26:28.080 --> 01:26:35.040
We waited and waited. It was now very foggy. There was no sound from the house.

01:26:36.080 --> 01:26:43.520
Then suddenly we heard something. Said Holmes. It's Sir Henry. Here he is at last.

01:26:46.240 --> 01:26:50.800
Sir Henry passed us. He walked quickly and he looked worried.

01:26:52.000 --> 01:27:00.000
Then we heard another sound. It was the sound of feet. But the feet weren't those of a man.

01:27:00.720 --> 01:27:07.360
They were those of a gigantic animal. Can you hear it? There's something there. Something's

01:27:07.360 --> 01:27:14.320
coming towards us. Look out. It's coming. Lestrade screamed and I took out my gun.

01:27:15.280 --> 01:27:22.560
Then out of the fog came a horrible animal. It was a gigantic black dog.

01:27:23.680 --> 01:27:29.280
But this wasn't an ordinary dog. It was a horrible gigantic hound.

01:27:30.480 --> 01:27:38.240
It was the hound of the Baskervilles. There was green light around its mouth. In its eyes there

01:27:38.320 --> 01:27:41.280
was green fire. We were terrified.

01:27:42.720 --> 01:27:46.880
It's chasing Sir Henry. Said Holmes. Your gun. Kill it.

01:27:48.000 --> 01:27:55.600
I fired my gun. There was a howl. The animal was hurt. We ran towards the sound. The gigantic

01:27:55.600 --> 01:28:02.400
hound was dead. Sir Henry was on the ground, terrified and pale. But he was alive.

01:28:03.280 --> 01:28:10.080
I gave him some brandy. Thank you, Watson. He said, but what was that animal? What was it?

01:28:10.880 --> 01:28:15.200
Its eyes and its horrible mouth. They were green.

01:28:17.440 --> 01:28:25.840
I went to look at the animal. Around its eyes and its mouth, I saw something green. It was

01:28:25.920 --> 01:28:35.840
phosphorus. It's the hound of the Baskervilles. But now it's dead. You're free. Said Holmes.

01:28:36.560 --> 01:28:43.760
The green you saw was phosphorus. Phosphorus glows in the dark. Now, I'm sorry Sir Henry,

01:28:43.760 --> 01:28:48.800
but we must hurry. We haven't got a lot of time and we need to find our man.

01:28:49.360 --> 01:28:55.600
We went back towards Merepit House. The door was open. We ran inside.

01:28:55.600 --> 01:29:04.400
Then we heard a noise. It came from a room upstairs. We ran upstairs in the direction of the noise.

01:29:04.400 --> 01:29:10.720
Holmes opened the door of the room. There was Stapleton's wife. She was on the floor.

01:29:10.720 --> 01:29:13.360
She had a scuff round her mouth.

01:29:13.520 --> 01:29:18.000
Good God. Said Holmes. Quick. Help her.

01:29:19.040 --> 01:29:23.360
Thank you. She said, is he safe? Is Sir Henry safe?

01:29:24.320 --> 01:29:29.200
Yes. He's safe. I said. And the hound. Where is it?

01:29:30.320 --> 01:29:34.000
Don't worry. It's dead. Said Holmes.

01:29:34.880 --> 01:29:43.280
Thank God. But find him. Find my husband. He's a horrible man. He's cruel and evil.

01:29:43.280 --> 01:29:49.760
He keeps his hound in the middle of the grimp and mire. That's where he is. Go and find him.

01:29:50.880 --> 01:29:54.480
But it's impossible with this fog. How can we find him?

01:29:55.760 --> 01:30:03.360
It's foggy, you say. That's good news. He ran to the center of the mire before the fog came down.

01:30:04.560 --> 01:30:11.040
He was able to get in there. But he can't get out now. He knows the way to the middle of the

01:30:11.040 --> 01:30:18.080
mire because of the rocks and plants. But in the fog, he can't get out. You've got him.

01:30:19.360 --> 01:30:22.960
And now I'm coming to the end of my strange story.

01:30:24.720 --> 01:30:31.840
The next morning it wasn't foggy. We went to the grimp and mire. We knew it was dangerous to

01:30:31.840 --> 01:30:36.640
cross it. But Mrs. Stapleton gave us directions and we followed them carefully.

01:30:37.680 --> 01:30:45.520
The path went left and then right. It was difficult to follow. Any mistake was certain death for us.

01:30:46.880 --> 01:30:52.160
Then suddenly we saw something in the mire. It was a shoe.

01:30:53.680 --> 01:30:58.880
Holmes took a stick and got the shoe. There was a label Meyers Toronto inside.

01:30:59.680 --> 01:31:01.840
It was Sir Henry's missing shoe.

01:31:03.920 --> 01:31:10.400
Stapleton used this shoe, said Holmes. His dog needed a scent to follow Sir Henry.

01:31:11.040 --> 01:31:13.520
This shoe gave the animal the scent.

01:31:15.600 --> 01:31:22.560
We arrived at the center of the mire. Stapleton wasn't there. But this was where the hound lived.

01:31:23.280 --> 01:31:27.360
There was some food and the dead body of a black and white dog.

01:31:28.800 --> 01:31:34.640
Look! A dead dog, said Holmes. Dr. Mortimer's dog.

01:31:36.320 --> 01:31:44.880
Poor animal and poor Mortimer. He loved his dog. Do you know Watson? I think Stapleton's dead.

01:31:45.520 --> 01:31:53.360
I think he died in the mire. This shoe is our proof. And this place is where Stapleton's hound lived.

01:31:54.480 --> 01:32:00.240
We all heard the sound of the hound on the moor. Stapleton could hide the hound,

01:32:00.960 --> 01:32:08.320
but he couldn't keep it quiet. I agreed with Holmes. Stapleton was probably dead.

01:32:09.280 --> 01:32:15.840
Back in Baker Street, London, it was the end of November. It was a cold, foggy night.

01:32:15.840 --> 01:32:19.120
Holmes and I were in the sitting room by the fire.

01:32:20.080 --> 01:32:26.560
It was good to see Sir Henry and Dr. Mortimer again. Wasn't it Holmes? I'm pleased they came this afternoon.

01:32:27.520 --> 01:32:32.560
Yes. I didn't know they were in London. It was good of them to come.

01:32:32.800 --> 01:32:38.160
It was a very interesting case, the case of their hound of the Baskavilles.

01:32:38.160 --> 01:32:44.240
Yes. But there are one or two things that I still don't understand.

01:32:45.920 --> 01:32:49.280
Let's go back to the beginning, said Holmes.

01:32:49.280 --> 01:32:56.240
First of all, the picture in the dining room. It showed us that Stapleton was a Baskaville.

01:32:56.240 --> 01:33:01.600
He was the son of Roger Baskaville, Sir Charles' third brother.

01:33:01.600 --> 01:33:08.960
Roger died in South America. We all thought Roger wasn't married, but that wasn't true.

01:33:09.600 --> 01:33:16.480
He got married and had a son. His son's name was also Roger, our man Stapleton.

01:33:17.520 --> 01:33:24.320
Years later, young Roger got married. He married Beryl Garcia, a beautiful woman from Costa Rica.

01:33:24.960 --> 01:33:33.360
Roger was a bad man, like his father. He stole a lot of money. The police wanted to talk to him,

01:33:33.360 --> 01:33:40.080
so he changed his name to Vandellur. Mr. and Mrs. Vandellur escaped to England.

01:33:40.080 --> 01:33:47.520
Here, they started their school in the north. Then, when the three schoolboys died, the Vandellurs

01:33:47.520 --> 01:33:53.200
changed their name again to Stapleton. They went to Dartmoor.

01:33:53.200 --> 01:34:00.160
Stapleton knew he was a Baskaville. He knew Sir Charles was rich.

01:34:01.200 --> 01:34:05.760
He decided to kill Sir Charles. Beryl pretended to be Stapleton's sister,

01:34:05.760 --> 01:34:12.480
and they bought a house near Baskaville Hall. Here, Stapleton became friends with Sir Charles

01:34:12.480 --> 01:34:19.600
Baskaville. Sir Charles told him about the hound of the Baskavilles. Stapleton knew that Sir Charles

01:34:19.600 --> 01:34:24.320
was afraid of the hound, and he knew that Sir Charles had a weak heart.

01:34:25.440 --> 01:34:33.280
This gave Stapleton the idea. He went to London and bought a gigantic dog. It was strong and

01:34:33.280 --> 01:34:41.520
savage. He took it to Dartmoor in secret. As we know, it lived at the Grimp and Meyer.

01:34:42.240 --> 01:34:48.320
This is why people sometimes heard the hound. The idea of the phosphorus was very clever.

01:34:48.880 --> 01:34:52.080
The dog looked evil. It looked supernatural.

01:34:54.000 --> 01:35:01.200
Sometimes, Stapleton took the dog onto the moor at night. People saw it, and began to talk about

01:35:01.200 --> 01:35:08.160
the curse of the hound of the Baskavilles. Stapleton really wanted Sir Charles to see the hound,

01:35:08.160 --> 01:35:14.800
but Sir Charles never went onto the moor at night. He was afraid. So, Stapleton asked Beryl to help

01:35:14.800 --> 01:35:20.160
him, but she refused. That's when Laura Lyons comes into the story.

01:35:21.040 --> 01:35:27.600
Stapleton became friends with her. She thought he was a single man. She wanted to divorce her

01:35:27.600 --> 01:35:35.040
horrible husband and marry Stapleton. Then, Stapleton heard about Sir Charles's trip to London.

01:35:35.600 --> 01:35:42.320
He worked very fast. He told Laura to write to Sir Charles. He told her to ask for a meeting.

01:35:43.040 --> 01:35:49.120
He gave the letter to Sir Charles. Then, he made up a story and told Laura not to go.

01:35:50.560 --> 01:35:57.360
That night, Stapleton went to the Grimp and Meyer. He painted the hound's eyes and mouth with the

01:35:57.360 --> 01:36:05.120
phosphorus. Then, he took the dog to the moor gate. Here, it jumped over the gate and chased Sir Charles.

01:36:05.920 --> 01:36:12.320
Sir Charles died of fright. The dog didn't run on the path. It ran next to the path.

01:36:13.040 --> 01:36:19.520
That's why there were no footprints until the end. Then, Stapleton called the dog and he took it back

01:36:19.520 --> 01:36:27.680
to the mire. He was very clever. There was no proof. His wife and Laura Lyons thought something was

01:36:27.680 --> 01:36:35.360
wrong, but they didn't have any proof. At first, Stapleton probably didn't know anything

01:36:35.360 --> 01:36:43.360
about Sir Henry. But after Sir Charles's death, Dr Mortimer told him. He told him about the Canadian

01:36:43.360 --> 01:36:50.720
air. Dr Mortimer came to London and Stapleton followed with his wife. He couldn't leave her on

01:36:50.720 --> 01:36:57.680
Dartmoor. He didn't trust her. He locked her in the hotel room. He followed Dr Mortimer

01:36:57.680 --> 01:37:05.600
every day. He wore a big black beard. It was a false beard. That day, he followed Dr Mortimer

01:37:05.600 --> 01:37:11.920
here to Baker Street. Then, he followed him to the station. He saw Sir Henry and the doctor go to

01:37:11.920 --> 01:37:18.560
the hotel. Stapleton probably wanted to kill Sir Henry here in London. When he saw us,

01:37:18.560 --> 01:37:26.400
he changed his plans. His wife knew about his plans. She wanted to tell Sir Henry,

01:37:26.400 --> 01:37:32.880
but she was afraid of her husband. She cut words from the front page of the time's newspaper to

01:37:32.880 --> 01:37:40.160
make a letter. A servant gave it to Sir Henry. Stapleton needed something with Sir Henry's

01:37:40.160 --> 01:37:47.520
scent on it. He needed it for the dog. He paid a servant in the hotel and the servant stole the

01:37:47.520 --> 01:37:54.800
shoe. But it was a new shoe. Sir Henry's scent wasn't on it. That's why the second shoe was missing.

01:37:56.240 --> 01:38:02.800
When Stapleton heard we were on the case, he went back to Dartmoor. That's where our story started.

01:38:04.240 --> 01:38:10.400
There's one thing I still don't understand, Holmes. Everyone knew Stapleton. Everyone knew his name.

01:38:10.960 --> 01:38:17.520
He couldn't suddenly become a Baskerville. Mrs. Stapleton told me he had many plans.

01:38:18.480 --> 01:38:24.480
One was to go back to South America. He didn't need to be in England to get the money. There were

01:38:24.480 --> 01:38:32.320
other plans too. But you can be sure Watson Stapleton knew how to get his money. He was an evil man.

01:38:33.920 --> 01:38:38.720
Now, Watson, let's talk about something different. I've got tickets for a show.

01:38:38.720 --> 01:38:45.360
Let's have dinner at Marcini's, then go to the theatre. Can you be ready in half an hour?

